language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 8: Integer Assignment Matrix
$
$ Domain:  matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..nGolfers)] of int(1..g)
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Each golfer gets a group number in 1..g each week
$   - Every golfer is assigned each week (the matrix is fully populated)
$
$ Information NOT carried (must be constrained explicitly):
$   - Group sizes: nothing prevents all golfers from being assigned to group 1
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   1. Group size constraint: each group has exactly s golfers each week
$   2. Pairing constraint: no pair of golfers shares a group more than once
$
$ Compared to Formulation 7 (matrix of functions):
$   - Same golfer-centric perspective, but the function abstraction is removed.
$   - With plain integers, we lose the typed function semantics.
$   - The constraints are identical to Formulation 7, but expressed using
$     matrix indexing rather than function application.
$   - This is a common "flat" encoding seen in many CP textbooks.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s

find sched : matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..nGolfers)] of int(1..g)

$ Group size constraint: each group has exactly s members each week
such that
    forAll i : int(1..w) .
        forAll j : int(1..g) .
            (sum p : int(1..nGolfers) . toInt(sched[i, p] = j)) = s,

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : int(1..nGolfers) .
        forAll p2 : int(1..nGolfers) .
            p1 < p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                toInt(sched[i, p1] = sched[i, p2])
            ) <= 1
